[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    1157[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe cold-start handling matters because every new role assignment is a cold start. A nurse who transfers from cardiology to oncology has a perfectly good baseline for "cardiology nurse activity" and a useless one for "oncology nurse activity," and the detector needs to avoid producing six weeks of false positives during the transition. The peer-group fallback gives a reasonable starting point; the per-user baseline takes over once enough data accumulates. Programs that don't handle cold-start gracefully end up with a flood of "anomaly" alerts every time someone changes role, which trains the privacy office to ignore the system.[K
